modules.name: AWS.ResourceGroups
modules.comments:
AWS Resource Groups

AWS Resource Groups lets you organize AWS resources such as Amazon EC2 instances, Amazon Relational Database Service databases, and Amazon S3 buckets into groups using criteria that you define as tags. A resource group is a collection of resources that match the resource types specified in a query, and share one or more tags or portions of tags. You can create a group of resources based on their roles in your cloud infrastructure, lifecycle stages, regions, application layers, or virtually any criteria. Resource groups enable you to automate management tasks, such as those in AWS Systems Manager Automation documents, on tag-related resources in AWS Systems Manager. Groups of tagged resources also let you quickly view a custom console in AWS Systems Manager that shows AWS Config compliance and other monitoring data about member resources.

To create a resource group, build a resource query, and specify tags that identify the criteria that members of the group have in common. Tags are key-value pairs.

For more information about Resource Groups, see the AWS Resource Groups User Guide.

AWS Resource Groups uses a REST-compliant API that you can use to perform the following types of operations.

  • Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD) operations on resource groups and resource query entities

  • Applying, editing, and removing tags from resource groups

  • Resolving resource group member ARNs so they can be returned as search results

  • Getting data about resources that are members of a group

  • Searching AWS resources based on a resource query

declarations.comments: Creates a group with a specified name, description, and resource query.
declarations.title: createGroup

declarations.comments: Deletes a specified resource group. Deleting a resource group does not delete resources that are members of the group; it only deletes the group structure.
declarations.title: deleteGroup

declarations.comments: Returns information about a specified resource group.
declarations.title: getGroup

declarations.comments: Returns the resource query associated with the specified resource group.
declarations.title: getGroupQuery

declarations.comments: Returns a list of tags that are associated with a resource, specified by an ARN.
declarations.title: getTags

declarations.comments: Returns a list of ARNs of resources that are members of a specified resource group.
declarations.title: listGroupResources

declarations.comments: Returns a list of existing resource groups in your account.
declarations.title: listGroups

declarations.comments: Returns a list of AWS resource identifiers that matches a specified query. The query uses the same format as a resource query in a CreateGroup or UpdateGroupQuery operation.
declarations.title: searchResources

declarations.comments: Adds specified tags to a resource with the specified ARN. Existing tags on a resource are not changed if they are not specified in the request parameters.
declarations.title: tag

declarations.comments: Deletes specified tags from a specified resource.
declarations.title: untag

declarations.comments: Updates an existing group with a new or changed description. You cannot update the name of a resource group.
declarations.title: updateGroup

declarations.comments: Updates the resource query of a group.
declarations.title: updateGroupQuery

declarations.comments: The request does not comply with validation rules that are defined for the request parameters.
declarations.title: BadRequestException

declarations.comments: The caller is not authorized to make the request.
declarations.title: ForbiddenException

declarations.comments: A resource group.
declarations.title: Group

declarations.comments: The underlying resource query of a resource group. Resources that match query results are part of the group.
declarations.title: GroupQuery

declarations.comments: An internal error occurred while processing the request.
declarations.title: InternalServerErrorException

declarations.comments: The request uses an HTTP method which is not allowed for the specified resource.
declarations.title: MethodNotAllowedException

declarations.comments: One or more resources specified in the request do not exist.
declarations.title: NotFoundException

declarations.comments: The ARN of a resource, and its resource type.
declarations.title: ResourceIdentifier

declarations.comments: The query that is used to define a resource group or a search for resources.
declarations.title: ResourceQuery

declarations.comments: The caller has exceeded throttling limits.
declarations.title: TooManyRequestsException

declarations.comments: The request has not been applied because it lacks valid authentication credentials for the target resource.
declarations.title: UnauthorizedException
